 national development and international competition, and whether higher education should be supported by public funds, especially in periods of fiscal austerity. The history of capitalism and the history of the university, Nelson reveals, are intimately intertwined—which raises a host of important questions that remain salient today. How do we understand knowledge and education as commercial goods? Should they be public or private? Who should pay for them? And, fundamentally, what is the optimal system of higher education for a capitalist democracy?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCapitalism and educationzUnited States. 0aCapitalismxSocial aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEducation, HigherxEconomic aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aEducation, HigherzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aEDUCATION / General.2bisacsh  aHarvard, University of Virginia, middle class, liberalism, public good, private good, meritocracy, commercialization, democratization, industrialization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311079731240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226829210423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226829210/original  a978-3-11-079731-2  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles